Computer Language: (("Teaching Languages" "Essentials of Programming Languages (3rd ed.)") #(#t trad-write mixed-fraction-e #f #t debug))
>Description:
When you select several rows, while holding shift pressing Home selects the part of the code, that is before the selection on the first row and not the part after the last selected character on the last row.

There is also some strange behaviour when you press first 'end' then 'home', while holding 'shift'
>How-To-Repeat:
select several rows from top to bottom (the selection of the first one should not be from the beginning of the row).

Press and hold shift, then press home.

The pattern from the description has occured.
>Fix:
>Audit-Trail:
From: Robby Findler <robby@eecs.northwestern.edu>
To: leh@abv.bg, bugs@racket-lang.org
Cc: nobody@racket-lang.org, bug-notification@racket-lang.org
Subject: Re: [racket-bug] all/11768: Navigation with <shift> + Home is broken
Date: Thu, 24 Feb 2011 07:20:29 -0600

 On Thu, Feb 24, 2011 at 7:00 AM,  <leh@abv.bg> wrote:
 > A new problem report is waiting at
 >  http://bugs.racket-lang.org/query/?cmd=view&pr=11768
 
 
 Hi: I'm having trouble understanding what you're seeing and what you'd
 like to see. Can you give me a concrete example to work with?
 
 To give you an idea of what I'm after, here's a concrete example of
 using shift-home that seems to work properly.
 
 1) open a new drracket window
 2) insert the following text:
 
 ---cut-here---
 11
 22
 33
 44
 ---cut-here---
 
 3) Put the insertion point between the two "4"s.
 4) type shift-up twice
 
 At this point, the text starting between the two "2"s and ending
 between the two "4"s is selected.
 
 5) type shift-home
 
 At this point, the entire line containing the "2"s is selected, and
 the selection continues to the same spot as before, namely between the
 two "4"s.
 
 This one example, at least, seems like the right behavior. Or were you
 saying that if you do those steps you also expect the second "4" to be
 selected in the last step?
 
 Robby

From: Robby Findler <robby@eecs.northwestern.edu>
To: Matthew Flatt <mflatt@cs.utah.edu>
Cc: bugs <bugs@racket-lang.org>
Subject: Re: Re: [racket-bug] all/11768: Navigation with <shift> + Home is broken
Date: Wed, 2 Mar 2011 07:26:57 -0600

 I think that the way to fix this is to make extendstartpos and
 extendendpos available via a method like get-position.
 
 I'm happy to make this change, and I think that there are a lot of
 methods that need to be using this instead of the position.
 
 The other alternative seems to be to try to generalize the
 move-position method, allowing it to take an absolute position or
 something like that, but after tracing thru the code, it appears that
 typing s:left invokes this method in a way that ends up being pretty
 simple so probably the right thing is to let others just look and see
 what extendstartpos and extendendpos are and then do something based
 on that.
 
 I think that probably extendendpos and extendstartpos need to be
 settable too, but I haven't gotten that far yet; only read the code.
 
 Anyways, does this sound like the right strategy?
 
 Robby
 
