From: Robby Findler <robby@eecs.northwestern.edu>
To: Ll Ss <leh@abv.bg>
Cc: bugs <bugs@racket-lang.org>
Subject: Re: Re: [racket-bug] all/11768: Navigation with <shift> + Home is broken
Date: Sun, 6 Mar 2011 08:20:02 -0600

 On Thu, Feb 24, 2011 at 7:56 AM, Ll Ss <leh@abv.bg> wrote:
 > Hi,
 >
 > There is some king of misunderstanding here. Maybe I didn't provide clear
 > enough explanation. Here are the steps to reproduce the problem and some
 > screenshots.
 
 Thank you for the very clear explanation!
 
 > 1) In the definition window mark code at least 2 rows long without using
 > your mouse. Instead use your keyboard by holding down the shift key and
 > using the up/down arrows. Start marking from top to bottom. See Screenshot1
 >
 > 2) Now if you press and hold shift and press the left/right arrow, you will
 > see, that you can select/deselect characters from the last marked row. See
 > Screenshot 2. So the cursor is placed on the last selected row and if I
 > press 'END' button it should mark the line till the end. This is working as
 > expected.
 >
 > 3) But if you try to DESELECT the last selected line to it's beginning, by
 > pressing the 'HOME' button, the row on the top is marked to the beginning.
 >
 > So what I see is this: Screenshot3 (look at the top left corner in Scr3) but
 > I expected this: Screenshot4 (look at the bottom left corner of Scr4).
 >
 
 The biggest problem here is that the keybindings are implemented at
 two layers of the system and the lower layer has access to state that
 makes it possible to implement the shift-based movement keys, but the
 upper layer is where shift-home is implemented. So I'll fix that (and
 there are lots of other keybindings that are wrong a manner similar to
 what you describe for shift-home and shift-end).
 
 Meanwhile, I would expect that, in step 3, to get something different.
 First: did you mean shift home? Assuming so, I would think that the
 home key would decide to try to include the "(defi" from the beginning
 of the selection, ie to try to include the line starting from the
 beginning of the selection. Thus you'd end up with only the "(defi"
 selected (because, back in step 1, you started with the insertion
 point between the "i" and the "n" and did shift-down).
 
 That is, you'd get the  same thing as if you used shift-up and
 shift-left to get to the beginning of the first line, not the
 beginning of the last line.
 
 Do you agree? If not, how does DrRacket know you mean the beginning of
 the last line instead of the beginning of the first line? (Or am I
 missing something more fundamental?)
 
 Thanks,
 Robby
From: Ll Ss <leh@abv.bg>
